        1. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/css/
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The following directives either allow wildcard sources (or ancestors), are not defined, or are overly broadly defined:

          frame-ancestors, form-action

          The directive(s): frame-ancestors, form-action are among the directives that do not fallback to default-src, missing/excluding them is the same as allowing anything.

          frame-ancestors, form-action

          The directive(s): frame-ancestors, form-action are among the directives that do not fallback to default-src, missing/excluding them is the same as allowing anything.

          default-src 'none'; style-src 'unsafe-inline'; img-src data:; connect-src 'self'
          Solution

          Ensure that your web server, application server, load balancer, etc. is properly configured to set the Content-Security-Policy header.
        3. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/buttons/
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The following directives either allow wildcard sources (or ancestors), are not defined, or are overly broadly defined:

          frame-ancestors, form-action

          The directive(s): frame-ancestors, form-action are among the directives that do not fallback to default-src, missing/excluding them is the same as allowing anything.

          Evidence 
          default-src 'none'; style-src 'unsafe-inline'; img-src data:; connect-src 'self'
          Solution

          Ensure that your web server, application server, load balancer, etc. is properly configured to set the Content-Security-Policy header.
        4. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/index.php
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The following directives either allow wildcard sources (or ancestors), are not defined, or are overly broadly defined:

          frame-ancestors, form-action

          The directive(s): frame-ancestors, form-action are among the directives that do not fallback to default-src, missing/excluding them is the same as allowing anything.

          default-src 'none'; style-src 'unsafe-inline'; img-src data:; connect-src 'self'
          Solution

          Ensure that your web server, application server, load balancer, etc. is properly configured to set the Content-Security-Policy header.
        5. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/js/
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The following directives either allow wildcard sources (or ancestors), are not defined, or are overly broadly defined:

          frame-ancestors, form-action

          The directive(s): frame-ancestors, form-action are among the directives that do not fallback to default-src, missing/excluding them is the same as allowing anything.

          default-src 'none'; style-src 'unsafe-inline'; img-src data:; connect-src 'self'
          Solution

          Ensure that your web server, application server, load balancer, etc. is properly configured to set the Content-Security-Policy header.
        6. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/nivo-slider/
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The following directives either allow wildcard sources (or ancestors), are not defined, or are overly broadly defined:

          frame-ancestors, form-action

          The directive(s): frame-ancestors, form-action are among the directives that do not fallback to default-src, missing/excluding them is the same as allowing anything.

          Solution

          Ensure that your web server, application server, load balancer, etc. is properly configured to set the Content-Security-Policy header.
        7. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/nivo-slider/themes/
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The following directives either allow wildcard sources (or ancestors), are not defined, or are overly broadly defined:

          frame-ancestors, form-action

          The directive(s): frame-ancestors, form-action are among the directives that do not fallback to default-src, missing/excluding them is the same as allowing anything.

          default-src 'none'; style-src 'unsafe-inline'; img-src data:; connect-src 'self'
          Solution

          Ensure that your web server, application server, load balancer, etc. is properly configured to set the Content-Security-Policy header.
        8. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/nivo-slider/themes/default/
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The following directives either allow wildcard sources (or ancestors), are not defined, or are overly broadly defined:

          frame-ancestors, form-action

          The directive(s): frame-ancestors, form-action are among the directives that do not fallback to default-src, missing/excluding them is the same as allowing anything.

          Evidence 
          default-src 'none'; style-src 'unsafe-inline'; img-src data:; connect-src 'self'
          Solution

          Ensure that your web server, application server, load balancer, etc. is properly configured to set the Content-Security-Policy header.
        9. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/robots.txt
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The following directives either allow wildcard sources (or ancestors), are not defined, or are overly broadly defined:

          frame-ancestors, form-action

          The directive(s): frame-ancestors, form-action are among the directives that do not fallback to default-src, missing/excluding them is the same as allowing anything.

          Evidence 
          default-src 'none'; style-src 'unsafe-inline'; img-src data:; connect-src 'self'
          Solution

          Ensure that your web server, application server, load balancer, etc. is properly configured to set the Content-Security-Policy header.
        10. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/sitemap.xml
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The following directives either allow wildcard sources (or ancestors), are not defined, or are overly broadly defined:

          frame-ancestors, form-action

          The directive(s): frame-ancestors, form-action are among the directives that do not fallback to default-src, missing/excluding them is the same as allowing anything.

          Evidence 
          default-src 'none'; style-src 'unsafe-inline'; img-src data:; connect-src 'self'
          Solution

          Ensure that your web server, application server, load balancer, etc. is properly configured to set the Content-Security-Policy header.
      3. Cross-Domain Misconfiguration (33)
        1. GET https://dvwa.co.uk
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        2. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        3. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/css
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        5. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/css/all.css
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Solution

        6. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/css/lt7.css
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        9. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.

        11. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/buttons
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        13. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/buttons/bugs.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        14. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/buttons/download.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        15. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/buttons/source.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        16. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/buttons/wiki.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        17. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/slider1.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        18. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/slider2.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        19. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/slider3.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        20. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/index.php
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

      <h1>404</h1>
      <p><strong>File not found</strong></p>

      <p>
        The site configured at this address does not
        contain the requested file.
      </p>

      <p>
        If this is your site, make sure that the filename case matches the URL.<br>
        For root URLs (like <code>http://example.com/</code>) you must provide an
        <code>index.html</code> file.
      </p>

      <p>
        <a href="https://help.github.com/pages/">Read the full documentation</a>
        for more information about using <strong>GitHub Pages</strong>.
      </p>

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        21. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/js
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

        The site configured at this address does not
        contain the requested file.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        23. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/js/jquery-1.6.2.min.js
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

      <p><strong>File not found</strong></p>

      <p>
        The site configured at this address does not
        contain the requested file.
      </p>

      <p>
        If this is your site, make sure that the filename case matches the URL.<br>
        For root URLs (like <code>http://example.com/</code>) you must provide an
        <code>index.html</code> file.
      </p>

          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        27. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/nivo-slider/themes
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        29. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/nivo-slider/themes/default
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        31. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/nivo-slider/themes/default/default.css
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.
        33. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/sitemap.xml
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          Alert description

          Web browser data loading may be possible, due to a Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) misconfiguration on the web server
          Other info

          The CORS misconfiguration on the web server permits cross-domain read requests from arbitrary third party domains, using unauthenticated APIs on this domain. Web browser implementations do not permit arbitrary third parties to read the response from authenticated APIs, however. This reduces the risk somewhat. This misconfiguration could be used by an attacker to access data that is available in an unauthenticated manner, but which uses some other form of security, such as IP address white-listing.

          Evidence 
          Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
          Solution

          Ensure that sensitive data is not available in an unauthenticated manner (using IP address white-listing, for instance).

          Configure the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" HTTP header to a more restrictive set of domains, or remove all CORS headers entirely, to allow the web browser to enforce the Same Origin Policy (SOP) in a more restrictive manner.

          Parameter 
          X-Frame-Options
          Solution

          Most modern Web browsers support the X-Frame-Options HTTP header. Ensure it's set on all web pages returned by your site (if you expect the page to be framed only by pages on your server (e.g. it's part of a FRAMESET) then you'll want to use SAMEORIGIN, otherwise if you never expect the page to be framed, you should use DENY. Alternatively consider implementing Content Security Policy's "frame-ancestors" directive.

      2. X-Content-Type-Options Header Missing (16)
        1. GET https://dvwa.co.uk
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Parameter 
          X-Content-Type-Options
          Solution

          Ensure that the application/web server sets the Content-Type header appropriately, and that it sets the X-Content-Type-Options header to 'nosniff' for all web pages.

          If possible, ensure that the end user uses a standards-compliant and modern web browser that does not perform MIME-sniffing at all, or that can be directed by the web application/web server to not perform MIME-sniffing.
        4. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/css/lt7.css
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Parameter 
          X-Content-Type-Options
          Solution

          Ensure that the application/web server sets the Content-Type header appropriately, and that it sets the X-Content-Type-Options header to 'nosniff' for all web pages.

          If possible, ensure that the end user uses a standards-compliant and modern web browser that does not perform MIME-sniffing at all, or that can be directed by the web application/web server to not perform MIME-sniffing.
        5. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/css/nivo-slider.css
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Parameter 
          X-Content-Type-Options
          Solution

          Ensure that the application/web server sets the Content-Type header appropriately, and that it sets the X-Content-Type-Options header to 'nosniff' for all web pages.

          If possible, ensure that the end user uses a standards-compliant and modern web browser that does not perform MIME-sniffing at all, or that can be directed by the web application/web server to not perform MIME-sniffing.
        7. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/buttons/bugs.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Parameter 
          X-Content-Type-Options
          Solution

          Ensure that the application/web server sets the Content-Type header appropriately, and that it sets the X-Content-Type-Options header to 'nosniff' for all web pages.

          If possible, ensure that the end user uses a standards-compliant and modern web browser that does not perform MIME-sniffing at all, or that can be directed by the web application/web server to not perform MIME-sniffing.
        8. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/buttons/download.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Parameter 
          X-Content-Type-Options
          Solution

          Ensure that the application/web server sets the Content-Type header appropriately, and that it sets the X-Content-Type-Options header to 'nosniff' for all web pages.

          If possible, ensure that the end user uses a standards-compliant and modern web browser that does not perform MIME-sniffing at all, or that can be directed by the web application/web server to not perform MIME-sniffing.
        9. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/buttons/source.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Parameter 
          X-Content-Type-Options
          Solution

          Ensure that the application/web server sets the Content-Type header appropriately, and that it sets the X-Content-Type-Options header to 'nosniff' for all web pages.

          If possible, ensure that the end user uses a standards-compliant and modern web browser that does not perform MIME-sniffing at all, or that can be directed by the web application/web server to not perform MIME-sniffing.
        10. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/buttons/wiki.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Parameter 
          X-Content-Type-Options
          Solution

          Ensure that the application/web server sets the Content-Type header appropriately, and that it sets the X-Content-Type-Options header to 'nosniff' for all web pages.

          If possible, ensure that the end user uses a standards-compliant and modern web browser that does not perform MIME-sniffing at all, or that can be directed by the web application/web server to not perform MIME-sniffing.
        11. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/slider1.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Parameter 
          X-Content-Type-Options
          Solution

          Ensure that the application/web server sets the Content-Type header appropriately, and that it sets the X-Content-Type-Options header to 'nosniff' for all web pages.

          If possible, ensure that the end user uses a standards-compliant and modern web browser that does not perform MIME-sniffing at all, or that can be directed by the web application/web server to not perform MIME-sniffing.
        12. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/slider2.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Parameter 
          X-Content-Type-Options
          Solution

          Ensure that the application/web server sets the Content-Type header appropriately, and that it sets the X-Content-Type-Options header to 'nosniff' for all web pages.

          If possible, ensure that the end user uses a standards-compliant and modern web browser that does not perform MIME-sniffing at all, or that can be directed by the web application/web server to not perform MIME-sniffing.
        13. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/images/slider3.png
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Parameter 
          X-Content-Type-Options
          Solution

          Ensure that the application/web server sets the Content-Type header appropriately, and that it sets the X-Content-Type-Options header to 'nosniff' for all web pages.

          If possible, ensure that the end user uses a standards-compliant and modern web browser that does not perform MIME-sniffing at all, or that can be directed by the web application/web server to not perform MIME-sniffing.
        14. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/js/jquery-1.6.2.min.js
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Parameter 
          X-Content-Type-Options
          Solution

          Ensure that the application/web server sets the Content-Type header appropriately, and that it sets the X-Content-Type-Options header to 'nosniff' for all web pages.

          If possible, ensure that the end user uses a standards-compliant and modern web browser that does not perform MIME-sniffing at all, or that can be directed by the web application/web server to not perform MIME-sniffing.
        15. GET https://dvwa.co.uk/js/jquery.nivo.slider.pack.js
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

Appendix

Alert types

This section contains additional information on the types of alerts in the report.

  1. CSP: Wildcard Directive

    Source raised by a passive scanner (CSP)
    CWE ID 693
    WASC ID 15
    Reference
    1. http://www.w3.org/TR/CSP2/
    2. http://www.w3.org/TR/CSP/
    3. http://caniuse.com/#search=content+security+policy
    4. http://content-security-policy.com/
    5. https://github.com/shapesecurity/salvation
    6. https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/security/csp#policy_applies_to_a_wide_variety_of_resources

  2. CSP: style-src unsafe-inline

    Source raised by a passive scanner (CSP)
    CWE ID 693
    WASC ID 15
    Reference
    1. http://www.w3.org/TR/CSP2/
    2. http://www.w3.org/TR/CSP/
    3. http://caniuse.com/#search=content+security+policy
    4. http://content-security-policy.com/
    5. https://github.com/shapesecurity/salvation
    6. https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/security/csp#policy_applies_to_a_wide_variety_of_resources

  3. Cross-Domain Misconfiguration

    Source raised by a passive scanner (Cross-Domain Misconfiguration)
    CWE ID 264
    WASC ID 14
    Reference
    1. https://vulncat.fortify.com/en/detail?id=desc.config.dotnet.html5_overly_permissive_cors_policy
